# Module Development Rules

## Module Structure

<module_structure>
- Create module in `modules/mod-<name>/` directory
- Required files: CMakeLists.txt, conf/<name>.conf.dist, src/<name>.cpp, src/<name>.h, README.md
- Database files: data/sql/base/ (schema), data/sql/updates/ (changes)
- Use create_module.sh script to generate base structure
- Follow naming conventions: PascalCase for classes, camelCase for functions
</module_structure>

## CMakeLists.txt

<cmake_rules>
- Set MODULE_NAME to match module name
- List all source files in SOURCES variable
- List all header files in HEADERS variable
- Set proper include directories
- Verify all files are listed (missing files cause compilation errors)
- Test compilation: `cmake .. && make -j$(nproc)`
- Check for compilation warnings
</cmake_rules>

## Configuration Files

<config_rules>
- Create conf/<name>.conf.dist with all settings
- All settings must have safe defaults (usually disabled)
- Use descriptive setting names: `ModuleName.SettingName`
- Document all settings with comments
- Provide sensible default values
- Test configuration loading on startup
- Verify settings can be overridden via environment variables
</config_rules>

## Database Schema

<database_rules>
- Base schema in data/sql/base/db_world/base_<name>.sql
- Updates in data/sql/updates/db_world/YYYY_MM_DD_XX_description.sql
- Use proper naming conventions for tables
- Define primary keys and indexes
- Add comments explaining table purpose
- Test schema creation: `mysql ... < base_<name>.sql`
- Verify table structure: `DESCRIBE <table_name>`
</database_rules>

## C++ Implementation

<cpp_rules>
- Inherit from appropriate ScriptMgr class (WorldScript, CreatureScript, etc.)
- Implement required virtual functions
- Use sConfigMgr->GetBoolDefault() for configuration
- Log startup/shutdown messages
- Handle errors gracefully
- Follow AzerothCore C++ standards
- Add Doxygen-style comments for public functions
- Test module initialization on server startup
</cpp_rules>

## Documentation

<documentation_rules>
- Create comprehensive README.md
- Document all features clearly
- Include installation instructions
- Document all configuration options
- Provide usage examples
- Include troubleshooting section
- Link to related resources
- Keep documentation up-to-date with code
</documentation_rules>

## Testing & Verification

<testing_rules>
- Module must compile without errors
- Module must compile without warnings (if possible)
- Validate on production with backups and rollback plan, or on a separate staging machine if you maintain one
- Verify module loads on startup
- Check logs for initialization messages
- Test all configuration options
- Verify no conflicts with other modules
- Test database schema creation
- Verify functionality works as intended
</testing_rules>

## Compilation

<compilation_rules>
- Build in separate build directory: `mkdir build && cd build`
- Configure: `cmake .. -DCMAKE_INSTALL_PREFIX=../env/dist`
- Compile: `make -j$(nproc)`
- Check for errors and warnings
- Verify all source files compiled
- Deploy using the same production-safe practices as core changes
</compilation_rules>

## Common Issues

<common_issues>
- **Module doesn't compile**: Check CMakeLists.txt syntax, verify all source files exist
- **Module doesn't load**: Check server logs, verify database schema applied
- **Configuration not working**: Verify setting names match code, reload server after config changes
- **Database errors**: Check SQL syntax, verify table names match code
- **Conflicts with other modules**: Check for duplicate functionality, test modules individually
</common_issues>
